Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage`

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2. ViewModel with back command + unsaved-changes flag

```csharp
// EditProductViewModel.cs
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Back()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return;           // cancel navigation
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

## 3. Guard the hardware/gesture back too (Android swipe, etc.)

The custom `BackButtonBehavior.Command` only handles the Shell toolbar button. To also intercept system-back and swipe gestures, override `OnNavigating` in `AppShell`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior` with `TextOverride="Cancel"` replaces the default arrow with a "Cancel" label.
- Its `Command` handles the toolbar button tap; `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` catches hardware/gesture back.
- Always call `deferral.Complete()` whether you cancel or not — omitting it freezes navigation.
